Let $O$ be the circumcenter of triangle $ABC.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, G, H, F, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(110);
B = dir(20);
C = dir(-80);
G = (A + B + C)/3;
H = extension(A, A + foot(A,B,C), B, B + foot(B,C,A));
F = (G + H)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--foot(A,B,C));
draw(B--foot(B,C,A));
draw(C--foot(C,A,B));
draw(G--H);
draw(A--F);
draw(B--F);
draw(C--F);
draw(circle(O,abs(O - A)));

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, SW);
label("$G$", G, NW);
label("$H$", H, NE);
label("$F$", F, S);
label("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

By Apollonius's Theorem,
\begin{align*}
AG^2 + BG^2 + CG^2 &= \frac{2}{3} (AB^2 + AC^2 + BC^2) \\
&= \frac{2}{3} (a^2 + b^2 + c^2).
\end{align*}Also,
\begin{align*}
GH^2 &= \frac{9}{4} (R^2 - \frac{a^2 + b^2 + c^2}{4}) \\
&= \frac{9}{16} (4R^2 - a^2 - b^2 - c^2).
\end{align*}Since $F$ is the midpoint of $\overline{GH},$ $GF = \frac{1}{2} GH,$ so
\[GF^2 = \frac{1}{4} GH^2 = \frac{9}{64} (4R^2 - a^2 - b^2 - c^2).\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $AGF,$
\[AF^2 = AG^2 + GF^2 - 2 \cdot AG \cdot GF \cdot \cos \angle AGF.\]Since $\angle AGF = \angle BHC,$
\[\cos \angle AGF = \cos \angle BHC = \frac{BH^2 + CH^2 - BC^2}{2 \cdot BH \cdot CH}.\]Let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $A$ to $\overline{BC}.$

